##With the outbreak of new crown disease, vulnerable children are the lucky ones

One piece of good news: Children may have survived the new crown disease. There have been no reports of children dying from the new coronavirus infection.

Of the 44,672 confirmed cases, 0.9 percent were infants under the age of 9, or about 400, according to data from the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention on Feb. 17. The proportion of patients under the age of 19 was 2.1 percent, or about 938 cases.

Previous incomplete statistics showed that 26.8 per cent of the confirmed cases of children nationwide had a history of exposure to the FOCI, and 71.2 per cent had a clear history of family clustering. It is concluded that close family contact is the main mode of infection of new coronavirus in children.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | proportion of newly diagnosed coronary disease in all age groups in China. Of the 44,672 patients diagnosed, 0.9% were infants under 9 years of age. (Source: China CDC Weekly)

Experts believe that from the distribution of the epidemic across the country, the number of cases reported by children has increased, mainly due to the gradual peak of the epidemic, the high incidence of family clusters of cases, the gradual popularization of pathogen testing, etc. , but the proportion of mild cases of infection is higher. The proportion of severe cases is much lower in children than in adults.

The clinical front line is very focused on the children in this outbreak. The Society of Pediatrics of the Chinese Medical Association and the Editorial Board of the Chinese Journal of Pediatrics have published online the first edition of the recommendations for the diagnosis, prevention and treatment of COVID-19 infection in children 2019 to guide rational clinical diagnosis and treatment. Recently, a series of relevant guidelines and suggestions have been issued in various places.

The symptoms are mild

The clinical manifestations of 134 confirmed cases of 285 children reported in China were analyzed. Most cases were mild, recovered quickly and had good prognosis. Fever and cough were common, there is fatigue, muscle pain, nasal congestion, Pharyngitis, headache, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain and diarrhea, and other manifestations, more than 1 week disappeared.

Of the 117 children with temperature records, 89 cases (76.1%) had high fever (11 cases) , moderate fever (17 cases) and low fever (61 cases) . There were 9 cases of asymptomatic infection (6.7%) , 87 cases of mild infection (64.9%) , 36 cases of common infection (26.9%) , including 7 cases of subclinical infection, 2 cases of severe infection (1.5%) and invasive mechanical ventilation (1.5%) .

Shanghai-based experts advise that fever and cough are common symptoms in children with new Crown Infections, but note the combination of digestive symptoms, diarrhea and vomiting. The clinical manifestations, course and prognosis of children and adults are different, and the mechanism is not clear.

Experts stressed that the majority of cases in children with asymptomatic and mild infections, clinical symptoms can not be mild or atypical, resulting in new coronavirus infection missed diagnosis and misdiagnosis. In addition, CT SCAN AND NUCLEIC ACID test should be complementary to each other because of the lack of specificity of CT SCAN in children with mild disease.

In the detection of virus nucleic acid, children's airway structure and epithelial cell function is different from that of adults, the reason of low ciliary clearance may also be a factor of low detection rate. For patients with mild illness, highly suspected patients or those with a history of close contact, the preferred sequence of specimen collection is nasopharyngeal swab, oropharyngeal Swab, sputum.

Figure | February 13, after more than two weeks of treatment, the country's first confirmed case of severe new crown pneumonia in children recovered and discharged. The child, aged 1 year and 2 months, lived in Huangpi District District, Wuhan. He suffered from intermittent diarrhea and vomiting for 6 days in the afternoon of January 26. Zhang Furong and others from the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Wuhan Children's Hospital reported the first case of critical illness in children in China. At 1 year old, the disease begins with gastrointestinal symptoms, with mild respiratory symptoms at early stage, rapidly progressing to Acute respiratory distress syndrome, septic shock, and acute renal failure. The child's first two throat swab nucleic acid tests were negative, until the 13th day of the onset of the third nucleic acid test was positive.

For the children with negative nucleic acid test, Zhang Furong et Al. speculate that, in addition to the children with sample collection and detection methods, it may also be related to the children with young, weak immune function, low viral load early infection. In addition, B ultrasound in children with hydronephrosis, can not rule out the presence of congenital hydronephrosis May.

Neonatal diagnosis

The first case of neonatal COVID-19 infection in China was a 17-day-old boy who "sneezed and vomited milk intermittently for a week, " according to a report by Liu Zhisheng and others at Wuhan Children's Hospital, on February 5,2020, she was admitted to the isolation ward of Neonatology Department of Wuhan Children's Hospital.

One Week before admission, the child appeared sneezing, accompanied by vomiting milk, no fever, cough and wheezing. Mental reaction decreased during the course of the disease, milk consumption decreased, urination and defecation were normal. On February 7, the throat swabs were positive for nucleic acid, but no anal swabs were detected. On February 8, both the throat swabs and anal swabs were positive for nucleic acid. On February 9, the throat swabs were negative for nucleic acid and the anal swabs were positive for nucleic acid.

The baby was admitted to the neonatal medical isolation ward for observation and treatment. The baby was kept warm and isolated in the incubator. Heart rate, respiration, blood pressure, blood sugar, in and out of the ward were closely monitored. The first day and the second day after admission, the child vomited, the third day began to ease, feeding well, the fourth day had a transient temperature of 37.8 degrees Celsius, accompanied by diarrhea, yellow loose stool 6 times a day, plus oral montmorillonite powder after the next day to return to normal. No cough, good appetite, stable vital signs, normal urine volume. No vomiting, fever, cough and dyspnea occurred 7 days after admission. Good appetite and no abnormal signs.

The parents of the children were newly diagnosed. Combined with the child's clinical manifestations, it suggests the presence of respiratory and digestive tract infection may be. The authors caution against oral transmission in home care, such as feeding, inadequate disinfection of utensils, and poor hand hygiene by caregivers, but do not rule out long-term lying position and swallowing of respiratory secretions.

After news reports of a 30-hour newborn diagnosed with a new crown infection, many were concerned about the possibility of vertical transmission of the virus from mother to child. If there is vertical mother-to-child transmission, then the pregnant woman to determine whether to terminate the pregnancy becomes a choice.

The Lancet published a small sample study from Wuhan on February 12 about pneumonia in The third trimester of pregnancy with COVID-19. There is no evidence that NCV infection can cause vertical transmission between mother and child, the study said.

Experts say it is not clear whether there is vertical transmission from mother to child, and newborns whose mothers have suspected or confirmed infections should be isolated for at least 14 days, during which direct breastfeeding is not recommended, breastfeeding is not feasible until new coronavirus infection has been excluded or cured.

Why children have milder symptoms

Why do children with novel coronavirus have less severe symptoms? There is no clear explanation.

WHO Director General Tan Desai said at a Feb. 17 briefing that statistics show that the risk of death increases with age. There are relatively few cases seen in children, and more research is needed to explain why.

The BBC and The New York Times report that scientists are more inclined to think that the immune system is under stress in adults who already have the disease, including those with diabetes or heart disease, they tend to be more vulnerable to such outbreaks.

That is, because adults already have other conditions, they are more affected than children, such as chickenpox, which is more dangerous in adults. Pneumonia, on the other hand, affects people with weakened immune systems.

SARS, Mers and other coronavirus infections have a similar pattern, with most infected children showing no symptoms. There were no child deaths in the 2003 SARS epidemic. The same is true of flu: Although thousands of young children are hospitalized each year, the death rate is low.

According to Luo Xiaoping, director of the Department of Pediatrics at Wuhan Tongji Hospital, generally speaking, high viral load is usually associated with its pathogenicity, but also with the infectivity of infected people. Scientists in China have identified the presence of a ACE2 protein that is needed for the new coronavirus to enter cells, at the same time, neocoronavirus appears to have evolved to hijack type 2 Alveolar epithelial cells for viral proliferation and transmission.

They believe that because of the wide distribution of ACE2 in the body, children are less susceptible to the new coronavirus, which the scientists speculate may be related to the development and function of the ACE2 protein, or differences in it, alternatively, ACE2-induced intracellular response in Alveolar epithelial cells of children is lower than that in adults. In addition, it has been clinically observed that NPV can deplete adult lymphocyte, whereas in children the WBC count and absolute lymphocyte are mostly normal without lymphocyte depletion, which may be related to the immaturity of their innate immunity.

It's always good to have mild childhood symptoms. But on the other hand, the fact that children infected with the new coronavirus have no symptoms or only mild symptoms raises another concern, namely, whether the infected, asymptomatic children will pass the virus on to others, children who do not realize they are infected may contribute to the spread of the epidemic.
